Juan Manuel Alvarez, convicted of causing a fatal Los Angeles train crash, faces a life sentence without parole as recommended by the jury.
Prosecutors argued Alvarez orchestrated the accident for attention, though defense claimed it was a suicide attempt gone wrong.
Despite the tragedy, Alvarez's wife showed support by withdrawing a restraining order.
The prosecution painted Alvarez as a troubled individual seeking his wife's attention through drastic measures.
Alvarez's troubled past, including abuse and trauma, shed light on his mental state during the incident.
The emotional trial highlighted the devastating impact on victims' families and Alvarez's tumultuous upbringing.
